import StarlightPage from '@astrojs/starlight/components/StarlightPage.astro';
---

<StarlightPage frontmatter={{ title: 'Reference' }}>
  <p>
    A tight cheatsheet. The things you keep needing to look up. Opinionated —
    "what I wish I knew a year ago."
  </p>

  <h2>Slash commands worth knowing</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <code>/clear</code> — wipes the conversation. Use it between unrelated
      tasks. Cheap context = better answers.
    </li>
    <li>
      <code>/init</code> — generates a starter <code>CLAUDE.md</code> for the
      current repo. Don't skip the human pass — Claude's first draft is rarely
      what you want long-term.
    </li>
    <li>
      <code>/cost</code> — shows your token usage for the session. Watch this
      when you're iterating on a big plan.
    </li>
    <li>
      <code>/agents</code> — manage subagents. Subagents = fresh context window
      for a sub-task. Huge for long sessions.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>File patterns that pay off</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>One CLAUDE.md per repo, plus a global <code>~/.claude/CLAUDE.md</code></strong>.
      Project rules go in the repo; personal preferences in global.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Issues - Pending Items.md</strong> — a project-root file where
      Claude logs unresolved questions. Saves you from "wait, what did I decide
      about X?" three weeks later.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Plan files (<code>docs/design/plan-*.md</code>)</strong> — write
      the plan before the code. Reviewing a plan is 10× cheaper than reviewing
      a diff.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Triage shortcuts</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>"Don't write code yet — just outline."</strong> Use this every
      time a feature touches more than one file.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>"List your assumptions before proceeding."</strong> Catches the
      AI's drift earlier than reading 200 lines of code.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>"What's the smallest change that makes this work?"</strong>
      Antidote to gold-plating.
    </li>
  </ul>

